'''Hantu''' is the [[Malay language|Malay]] and [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] word for spirit or ghost.<ref>{{cite book|title=Linguistik Indonesia|publisher=Yayasan Obor Indonesia|page=45|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BHraljbyOo0C&pg=PA45|accessdate=9 February 2017|language=id}}</ref> In modern usage it generally means spirits of the dead but has also come to erroneously refer to any legendary invisible being, such as demons.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Knappert|first1=Jan|title=Pacific Mythology: An Encyclopedia of Myth and Legend|publisher=Aquarian Press|isbn=9781855381339|page=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=q53fAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> In its traditional context the term also referred to animistic [[nature spirits]] or ancestral souls.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bane|first1=Theresa|title=Encyclopedia of Demons in World Religions and Cultures|date=2012|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786488940|page=162|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=njDRfG6YVb8C&pg=PA162|accessdate=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> The word is derived from [[Proto-Malayo-Polynesian]] ''*qanitu'' and [[Proto-Austronesian]] ''*qaNiCu''. [[Cognate]]s in other [[Austronesian people|Austronesian languages]] include the [[Micronesian people|Micronesian]] ''aniti'', [[Nage]] ''nitu'', [[Tao people|Tao]] ''anito'', [[Taivoan people|Taivoan]] ''alid'', [[Seediq people|Seediq]] and [[Atayal people|Atayal]] ''utux'', [[Bunun people|Bunun]] ''[[hanitu]]'' or ''hanidu'', [[Polynesian people|Polynesian]] ''[[aitu]]'' or ''[[atua]]'', and [[Tsou people|Tsou]] ''hicu'' among [[Taiwanese aborigines]].<ref name="apostol"/><ref name="baldick">{{cite book|editor =Julian Baldick|title =Ancient Religions of the Austronesian World: From Australasia to Taiwan|publisher =I.B.Tauris|series =|year =2013|page=3|isbn =9780857733573|url =https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=7U6oBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref name="funk">{{cite book|author=Leberecht Funk|editor = Y. Musharbash & G.H. Presterudstuen |title =Monster Anthropology in Australasia and Beyond|chapter =Entanglements between Tao People and Anito on Lanyu Island, Taiwan|publisher =Palgrave Macmillan|year =2014|pages=143–159|isbn =9781137448651|url =https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1057%2F9781137448651_9}}</ref> In terms of concept and place in traditional folklore, it is most similar to the Filipino [[anito]].
==Types== Aside from generic spirits of the dead, there exist various forms of hantu including both the benign and malevolent.
* [[Hantu Air]]: spirit inhabiting the water * Hantu Beruk: ape demon<ref name="skeat">{{cite book|last1=Skeat|first1=Walter William|title=Malay Magic: An Introduction To The Folklore And Popular Religion Of The Malay Peninsular|date=1965|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9780714620268|page=104|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K9Ly7Q9p-dgC&pg=PA104|accessdate=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> * Hantu Belian: tiger spirit<ref name="skeat"/> * Hantu Musang: a [[civet|civet cat]] spirit that is invoked in a game of [[demonic possession|possession]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brewster|first1=Paul G.|title=The Malayan Hantu Musang and Other Possession Games of Indonesia and Indochina|journal=Oriens|date=1 January 1958|volume=11|issue=1/2|pages=162–176|doi=10.2307/1578932|jstor=1578932}}</ref> * Hantu Pusaka: grave demon<ref>{{cite book|last1=Daniels|first1=Kimberly|title=The Demon Dictionary|date=2013|publisher=Charisma Media|isbn=9781621363002|page=151|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hYGjTDyFlxAC&pg=PA151|accessdate=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> * [[Hantu Raya]]: great demon.<ref name="skeat"/> This hantu is considered the strongest among evil spirits of the jungles of Malaysia, and takes the appearance of its owner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=TAJUDIN|first1=HAJI ZAIN|last2=LYMAN|first2=THOMAS A.|title=THE HANTU RAYA: A MALAY DEMON|url=http://siamese-heritage.org/jsspdf/1991/JSS_079_2e_ZainTajudin_HantuRayaMalayDemon.pdf|publisher=The Siamese Heritage Protection Program|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref> * Hantu Rimba: deep-forest demon<ref name="skeat"/> * [[Hantu Tinggi]]: tall demon, a demon that possesses a tree
