===Anime===
The first OVA, Mermaid Forest, was released in Japan in August 1991. A subtitled VHS release was released in North America by [[Central Park Media|US Manga Corps]] on March 3, 1993.<ref>{{cite journal |title=[[Animerica]] |volume=1 |issue=1 |date= March 1993 |page=18 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |issn=1067-0831}}</ref> It was marketed as one of the "Rumik World" anime (along with ''[[Maris the Chojo]]'', ''[[Fire Tripper]]'', and ''[[Laughing Target]]'').

''Mermaid's Scar'', was released in Japan on VHS and [[Laserdisc]] by [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]] on September 24, 1993.<ref>{{cite journal |title=[[Animerica]] |volume=1 |issue=7 |date=September 1993 |page=13 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |issn=1067-0831}}</ref> [[Viz media]] published a dubbed release on VHS on November 21, 1995.<ref>{{cite journal |title=[[Animerica]] |volume=3 |issue=11 |date=1995 |page=19 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |issn=1067-0831}}</ref>

In 2003 the animation company [[Tokyo Movie Shinsha]] produced a 13 episodes TV series based on Takahashi's short stories as part of the [[Takahashi Rumiko Gekijō]] series. All but ''Mermaid's Gaze'' were animated. While closely following the story of the original manga (more so than the [[OVA]] versions), many of the violent aspects of the stories were toned down. Only eleven episodes were shown on Japanese TV, with the final two episodes (''Mermaid's Scar'') released direct to video, allegedly because this particular story was too violent for TV. It was released in North America by [[Geneon]].

