'''Æthelwine''' (died 992) was [[ealdorman]] of [[East Anglia]] and one of the leading noblemen in the [[kingdom of England]] in the later 10th century. As with his kinsmen, the principal source for his life is [[Byrhtferth]]'s [[hagiography|life]] of [[Oswald of Worcester]]. Æthelwine founded [[Ramsey Abbey]] in 969,<ref>{{cite journal|first=Janet M.|last=Pope|title=Monks and Nobles in the Anglo-Saxon Monastic Reform|pages=166, 170|journal=Anglo-Norman Studies: Proceedings of the Battle Conference|volume=XVII|year=1994|editor-first=Christopher|editor-last=Harper-Brill|publisher=The Boydell Press|location=Woodbridge, UK|isbn=0 85115 606 1}}</ref> and Byrhtferth and [[Ramsey Abbey]] remembered him as ''Dei amicus'' (friend to God), but the monks of nearby [[Ely Cathedral|Ely]] saw him as an enemy who had seized their lands.

Æthelwine was a son of [[Æthelstan Half-King]], but probably not the eldest son as his brother [[Æthelwald, Ealdorman of East Anglia|Æthelwald]] seems to have succeeded their father on his retirement in 956. Æthelwine appears to have followed Æthelwald in office from 962. He was a benefactor of the [[New Minster]] at [[Winchester]], and of [[Ramsey Abbey]].

Following the death of King [[Edgar of England|Edgar]], Æthelwine was, with Oswald of Worcester and [[Dunstan]], a leader among the supporters of Edgar's oldest son [[Edward the Martyr|Edward]], which placed him in opposition to his former sister-in-law Dowager Queen [[Ælfthryth, Queen of England|Ælfthryth]] and [[Ælfhere, Ealdorman of Mercia]]. During the anti-monastic reaction in Edward's short reign, Æthelwine is portrayed as a stalwart supporter of the monks, but the record suggests that he took advantage of the weakness of royal government to dispossess the monks of Ely of lands.

Following the death of Ælfhere in 983, and the withdrawal of the queen-mother from court soon after the death of Bishop [[Æthelwald of Winchester]] in 984, Æthelwine became the leading lay figure at the court of the young King [[Æthelred the Unready|Æthelred]]. His death in 992 probably marks the beginning of Æthelred's personal reign.

Æthelwine's death is recorded by the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''. Byrhtferth provides more detail, reporting that, perhaps following a lengthy illness, Æthelwine was attended at his death by Germann, Abbot of Ramsey, and [[Alphege|Ælfheah]], later [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]. His remains were moved to Ramsey where the monks kept a vigil overnight before he was buried there.

The name of Æthelwine's wife is not recorded, but the names of three sons are known. Byrhtferth mentions Edwin; another son named Leofric appears to have witnessed a will in 986, while Æthelweard was killed fighting for [[Edmund Ironside]] at the [[battle of Ashingdon]] in 1016.

